## Paste‑Ready Narrative (Short Version)

> Monthly CS% and NICU% are derived from the NOH clinical outcomes dataset, with 3‑month rolling averages applied to reduce volatility from small monthly volumes. The data shows a clear step‑change from early programme performance into a persistently higher caesarean and NICU environment by 2024, with sustained CS elevation beginning in March 2024.  
>  
> Interpretation of this trend requires attention to intrapartum workforce conditions. Early programme phases relied on independent/private midwives for intrapartum support due to ward capacity constraints, while later phases depended on hospital ward midwives for intrapartum care. This transition increased sensitivity of outcomes to ward‑level staffing stability, confidence, and escalation culture.  
>  
> The key operational lesson is that improving outcomes requires ward‑level change management — including staffing continuity, capability development, and clear escalation expectations — rather than NOH team‑level interventions alone.

